  "text": "Using Eqs. (1), (2), (5), (7), and (12), we calculated the theoretical relationship between the true value of 1 H-C 2 and the apparent value that would be obtained from a twotime-point measurement for two values of DT and diamagnetic contaminations ranging from 0% to 5% (Fig. 6) . The apparent value C 2 is always smaller than the true value. For the case with R 2,dia = 50 s À1 , C 2 = 60 s À1 , and p d = 2%, the apparent value of C 2 from the two-time-point measurement with DT = 18 ms is 52 s À1 . For p d = 5%, the apparent value of C 2 is reduced to 44 s À1 . Note that the percentage error in C 2 is much larger than p d . This is due to the fact that the PRE significantly reduces the contribution of the first term in Eq. [CITATION_1] . The deviation from the true value of C 2 can be reduced by using a relatively small value of DT, thereby reducing the relative contribution of the second term. 15 N-HPr(E32C) conjugated with EDTA-Mn 2+ at Cys32. As expected from the above considerations, the measured C 2 values derived from the experiment with DT = 40 ms are systematically smaller than those obtained with DT = 4 ms, indicating the presence of a diamagnetic impurity. From this correlation, p d was estimated to be 3%. The same population for the diamagnetic impurity can also obtained from the intensities of residual peaks that should be completely broadened beyond detection, yet appear with low intensity because of the diamagnetic contamination (Fig. 7b) .",
